collation.p: VisColl collation. The collation reflects the current state of the manuscript. Several quires seem to have been placed in the wrong order, several quires together with many singletons are missing. For a reconstruction of the original structure see Testa (1992) .and this hypothethical VisColl collation.
collation.signatures: Quire signatures in Arabics numerals by a modern hand in the beginning of every quire.

p.note: Top of page, in black ink by a modern hand: Drottningholms Bibl. Kat. No 72.; 1854 20/8 (there also appears to be some erased writting in pencil next to this); centre page, in black ink by a modern hand: Från Kongl. Bibliotheket på Drottningholm till Kongl. Biblioteket; below: No 76: Etthundrade sextiosex Blad; bottom left corner, National Library book label with current signum.
Lower part of page: several lines of erased text in pencil by a modern or early modern hand. Text faintly visible, but not legible.
Bottom right corner, in pencil by a modern hand: omb. 1983 .

binding.p: Modern binding. The manuscript was rebound in 1983. Green velvet over wooden boards. 6 pairs of raised bands and endbands. , ink on a paperlabel: A 227.

origin.p: Flanders , 16th century, first quarter. The style of the decoration is Flemmish and has been ascribed to the workshop of Simon Bening. The manuscript is missing the calendar, which makes pinpointing the orgin of the intended user based on local saints dificult. The litany mentions St Gertrude (), which supports a Flemish origin. However, the inclusion of the prayer to St Sebald (), patron saint of Nuremberg, might contradict this. The masculine inflexions used in the prayers indicate that the manuscript was comissioned for a male user (ego sum facturus on ;, mihi miserrimo peccatori on ).

acquisition.p: Transferred from the library at Drottningholm Palace to the Royal Library in .

p.note: Scattered throughout the manuscript are numbers written in pencil by a modern hand (most likely by the bookbinder), e.g. bottom left corner. It is unclear what they refer to.

decoDesc.p: Main text in black ink, rubrics in red, some capitals touched in yellow/gold.
The manuscript originally contained numerous full- or half-page miniatures. Most of these have been removed and only four remain in the manuscript.
